In article <jktaberCMx2Dw.47x@netcom.com>, jktaber@netcom.com (John K. Taber) writes:
> :  How secure would be a 15 character random passphrase? I would work
> :  out the math, but, as some of you can probably tell, I'm not a
> :  mathematician. :)
> 
> 
> : ___ Blue Wave/QWK v2.12
> :                                 
> 
> I think you guys are still thinking "passwords".  I use key phrases.  I
> compose a short, original poem paying attention to metrics.  Because
> they must be one-liners they usually come out as epigrams.  These are
> easy to remember because of meter, so I never need to record them.
> Because they are original, they thwart a dictionary attack like running
> through the Oxford Book of English Verse.  My phrases are rather long
> because of the redundancy of natural languages, so that I need length
> to achieve an effective key length of say, 15-16 random characters.

Shannon showed that a 16 character English phrase has an information
content of about 1.3 bits per letter.  Better choose a pretty long
poem if you want 15*8 bits of randomness...
